observations.recommendation:
We recommended and the Local Chief Executive agreed to instruct the:
Inventory Committee to conduct a thorough physical inventory and submit the Report on the Physical Count of Property, Plant and Equipment with complete details not later than January 31 of each year;
Acting GSO to (i) maintain Property Cards for each type of properties in coordination with the Office of the Municipal Accountant; (ii) issue the corresponding Property Acknowledgement Receipt (PAR) to fixed the accountability of the end-user over the property; (iii) maintain Local Road Inventory and Road Map and Local Road Network Property Card; and (iv) take immediate action to ensure that registration and titling of the subject parcel of land in the name of the Municipality is undertaken;
Representative of any office receiving any property from any source secure all turnover documents or deed of donation from the donor and furnish the Accounting and GSO Office a copy for proper recognition of the same in the books of accounts simultaneous with the fixing of accountability therefor;
Municipal Engineering Office to provide the Municipal Accountant and the Acting GSO the complete description and cost segregation of road components for road projects and, on the basis of which, the Municipal Accountant to record the same in the books of accounts; and
Municipal Accountant to (i) setup and maintain a complete and accurate lapsing schedule for the PPE items to ensure the accuracy of the periodic depreciation charges for each PPE; (ii) prepare and maintain Property, Plant and Equipment Ledger Card (PPELC), and Real Property Ledger Card (RPLC); (iii) recognize donated properties in the books of accounts; and (iv) prepare Journal Entry Voucher (JEV) to recognize the depreciation expense and accumulated depreciation related to such assets, if applicable.
Management Comment: 	The representative of the concerned departments committed to furnish the Office of the Municipal Accountant with turn-over documents of donated properties received by them.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive:
instruct the Municipal Planning and Development Officer and Municipal Engineer to (i) ensure that all identified projects will be implemented without further delay; and (ii) continue to monitor and supervise the implementation of projects under the development fund;
direct the Local Development Council to (i) specify the projects, programs and activities under the Development fund; and (ii) stop the practice of lump sum budgeting and inclusion of generic items in the Annual Investment Plan and Annual Budget, otherwise secure prior authority from the Local Sanggunian;
ensure that all changes in the Annual Investment Program shall be reviewed and endorsed by the Local Development Council;
ensure that any change in the annual budget is supported with valid authority and documentation pursuant to Section 321 of R.A. 7160 and Section 454(2)(b) of its IRR; and
instruct the Municipal Accountant to (i) review the recognition of transactions for Infrastructure Accounts and draw correcting entries therefor; and (ii) reconcile his records with the Municipal Engineer and re-evaluate the nature and intent of expenditures in order to properly recognize all improvements made on various properties in the books of accounts and adjust the cost of PPE when applicable.

We recommended that the:
LDRRM Officer (i) prepare the LDRRMFIP in accordance with COA Circular 2012-002 showing, among others, the allocation of funds for every PPA, schedule of implementation, implementing office, expected output, funding source and expense class; (ii) include under a separate caption, the list of projects and activities charged to the unexpended LDRRMF of previous years; and (iii) allocate and utilize the LDRRMF with the PPAs specified in NDRRMC, DBM and DILG JMC No. 2013-1;
Management ensure compliance with the requirements set for all fund transfers related to LDRRMF;
MBO maintain a detailed RAAO based on the approved plan; and
Municipal Accountant (a) properly check the accuracy and completeness of all supporting documents before payment; (b) draw a Journal Entry Voucher to revert to the unappropriated surplus of the General Fund any unexpended LDRRMF after five years; and (c) prepare a note to financial statements pursuant to Section 5.1.16 of COA Circular 2012-002 to inform the users of the financial statement of the status of the LDRRMF as of reporting period.
Management Comment: 	The MDRRMO committed to prepare the necessary LDRRMFIP in accordance with the regulation. The Municipal Accountant, on the other hand, will prepare the notes to the financial statements of the municipality in the ensuing period.

We recommended and the Local Chief Executive agreed to direct the:
Chairman and Members of the BAC and TWG to (i) carefully scrutinize the documentary requirements submitted by bidder and conduct verification thereof to prevent any conflicting information thereon; and (ii) ensure the submission by the winning bidder of a valid performance security prior to the signing of the contract to safeguard the government from any untoward act of the former, if there be any;
Municipal Engineer to conduct close monitoring during project implementation and ensure compliance by the contractor with the requirements of the contract;
Municipal Accountant, in close coordination with the BAC, to (i) submit all the necessary supporting documents for the identified contracts; and (ii) verify all supporting documents as to the completeness before effecting payments thereof; and
Concerned Officials to ensure compliance with the reportorial requirements set by the oversight agency for Trust Funds.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive:
coordinate with the MCWMC to collect piled wastes observed during inspection and increase the daily or weekly collection volume to avoid the accumulation of mixed wastes inside the MRF;
through the MENRO and Liga ng mga Barangay, (i) encourage the active participation of barangay officials to support the solid waste management program of the government by educating their respective constituents on the proper segregation of reusable or recyclable materials from compostable wastes and coordinate efforts in the implementation of the five basic environmental laws; and (ii)  strengthen the implementation of existing ordinances and policies on solid waste management at the barangay level in order to achieve community compliance and eventually abide by the provisions on preserving and protecting the environment required under R.A. No. 9003;
as far as the Municipal budget permits, provide necessary support in enjoining barangays of the municipality to establish their own or clustered MRF; and
prioritize the presentation of the 10-year Solid Waste Management Plan for deliberation by the NSWMC to obtain its final approval.
Management Comment: The MENRO-Designate committed to exert his best effort to comply with the provisions of R.A. 9003.

