We recommended that the Members of the Local School Board:
Submit explanations and/or additional supporting documents to address the deficiencies on the SEF disbursements;
prepare a balanced budget with conscious and concerted efforts of observing compliance with the legal and regulatory requirements on SEF budgeting, allocation and utilization guidelines as prescribed under DepEd/DBM/ DILG Joint Circular 01 S 2017 and refrain from accommodating expenditures for activities for which the DepEd has the direct mandate to execute;
request for inputs from the Deped official/School Division Superintendent in the prioritization of SEF projects and expenditures in accordance with the DepEd criteria and with due regard to the provisions of laws, rules and regulations prescribing the limitations on the use of the fund;
maximize the utilization of SEF to attain its objectives, monitor the implementation of the PPAs, and take appropriate actions such as realignment or reprograming, if necessary;
observe the time-synchronized request for payments and require prompt submission of liquidation reports; and
ensure that all claims are supported by proper reports and comply with the required documentation for similar transactions in the future.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive
through the designated MENRO/Solid Waste Management Officer complete its 10-year Solid Waste Management Plan and seek approval from the National Solid Waste Management Commission;
through the Liga ng mga Barangay, encourage active participation of barangay officials to support the solid waste management program of the government by educating their respective constituents on the proper segregation of reusable or recyclable materials from compostable wastes and coordinate efforts in the implementation of the five basic environmental laws on preserving and protecting the environment required under R.A. No. 9003;
involve closely the Barangay officials and civic leaders in the strict implementation on the existing environmental laws and intensify the information campaign at the household level on the ordinances issued by the Municipality;
seek the help of private companies/organizations in the conduct of a more aggressive and intensive information campaign on the proper segregation of waste and “no littering” policies;
coordinate closely with the Provincial Government of Pampanga in the construction of the Materials Recovery Facility
limit access, repair fences and increase monitoring in the controlled dumpsite pending the establishment of the new MRF.

We recommended that the:
Local Chief Executive (i) prioritize the placement of a full-time MDRRM Officer to focus on core functions of the MDRRMO and the three mandatory staff personnel at the MDRRMO to handle the administration and training, research and planning, and operations and warning to effectively and efficiently address the requirements of the above-cited existing rules and regulations on disaster preparedness, mitigation, recovery and response; and (ii) as head of the LDC, fast track the preparation of the Municipality’s Comprehensive Development Plan (CDP) and Comprehensive Land-Use Plan (CLUP) in order that disaster risk management activities could be integrated to the development plan of the Municipality to prevent further loss of lives and properties;
Members of the MDRRMC (i) institute the functional organization of the ICS, the required training and resource management which include the personnel, teams, equipment, and other facilities available during emergencies, as a perfect tool in responding to all types of hazards most particularly in an on-scene emergency situations and calamities such as flooding; (ii) ensure that the member CSOs/NGOs to the Council possess the eligibility requirements cited under NDRRMC No.  3 to assure of effective and strengthened citizen’s participation in the locality;
MDRRMO prepare the monthly report on the sources and utilization of the LDRMMF and facilitate monitoring of the accomplishment vis-à-vis targeted projects for effective and efficient utilization of the Fund.

We recommended that the
Municipal Accountant (i) recognize all purchase of supplies stocks under the proper inventory account using the perpetual inventory system; and (ii) recognize supplies consumption monthly based on the SSMI with RIS submitted by the General Services Officer and;
General Services Officer (i) require the preparation of Requisition and Issue Slip (RIS) from end-users to support requisitions and issuance of supplies ; (ii) prepare SSMI supported with RIS for submission to the Municipal Accountant for proper recording; and (iii) conduct periodic inventory of supplies as prescribed by the above regulation.

